2 DETAILS VAN DE AANVRAAG EN TOELATING


2.1 Aanvraag

De toelating van het gewasbeschermingsmiddel Aliette WG is laatstelijk verlengd tot
1 oktober 2013. Het betreft een aanvraag tot herregistratie van de toelating van het middel Aliette WG (11561 N), een middel op basis van de werkzame stoffen fosetyl-aluminium. De herregistratie wordt aangevraagd voor de toelating als schimmelbestrijdingsmiddel in de onbedekte teelt van aardbeien en de teelt van witlof op water.


2.2 Informatie met betrekking tot de stof

De werkzame stof fosetyl-aluminium is bij Richtlijn 2006/64/EG, dd 18 juli 2006 van de Europese Commissie van de Europese Gemeenschappen opgenomen in Bijlage I van Richtlijn 91/414/EEG.


2.3 Karakterisering van het middel

Aliette WG is geformuleerd als een water dispergeerbaar granulaat dat 800 g/kg fosetyl-aluminium bevat. Fosetyl-Al behoort tot de chemische groep van de anorganische ethylfosfonaten. Aliette WG heeft een volledig systemische werking. Fosetyl-Al wordt in korte tijd opgenomen door de plant en verspreid middels acropetaal en basipetaal transport. Hierdoor wordt de gehele plant beschermd tegen indringers van buitenaf. Dit geldt ook voor nieuw gevormd blad en wortels. Aliette WG heeft aan de ene kant een directe werking op schimmels en aan de andere kant stimuleert Aliette WG het natuurlijk afweersysteem van de plant.


2.4 Voorgeschiedenis

De aanvraag is op 31 maart 2009 ontvangen; op 1 april 2009 zijn de verschuldigde aanvraagkosten ontvangen.


3 RISICOBEOORDELINGEN


Het gebruikte toetsingskader voor de beoordeling van deze aanvraag is weergegeven in de RGB (Hoofdstuk 2); te weten de werkinstructies RGB (voor toxicologie en milieu) en in de RGB aangeduide (delen van de) toepasselijke versie van de HTB ( in dit geval versie 1.0)



3.1 Fysische en chemische eigenschappen

De aard en de hoeveelheid van de werkzame stoffen en de in toxicologisch en ecotoxicologisch opzicht belangrijke onzuiverheden in de werkzame stof en de hulpstoffen zijn bepaald. De identiteit van het middel is vastgesteld. De fysische en chemische eigenschappen van het middel zijn vastgesteld en voor juist gebruik en adequate opslag van het middel aanvaardbaar geacht (artikel 28, eerste lid, sub c en e, Wet gewasbeschermingsmiddelen en biociden).

De beoordeling van de evaluatie van het middel en de stof staat beschreven in Hoofdstuk 2, Physical and Chemical Properties, in Bijlage II bij dit besluit.


3.2 Analysemethoden

De geleverde analysemethoden voldoen aan de vereisten. De residuen die het gevolg zijn van geoorloofd gebruik die in toxicologisch opzicht of vanuit milieu oogpunt van belang zijn, kunnen worden bepaald met algemeen gebruikte passende methoden (artikel 28, eerste lid, sub d, Wet gewasbeschermingsmiddelen en biociden).

De beoordeling van de evaluatie van de analysemethoden staat beschreven in Hoofdstuk 3, Methods of Analysis, in Bijlage II bij dit besluit.


3.3 Risico voor de mens

Het middel voldoet aan de voorwaarde dat het, rekening houdend met alle normale omstandigheden waaronder het middel kan worden gebruikt en de gevolgen van het gebruik, geen directe of indirecte schadelijke uitwerking heeft op de gezondheid van de mens. De voorlopige vastgestelde maximum residugehalten op landbouwproducten zijn aanvaardbaar (artikel 28, eerste lid, sub b, onderdeel 4 en sub f, Wet gewasbeschermingsmiddelen en biociden).
Het profiel humane toxicologie inclusief de beoordeling van het risico voor de toepasser staat beschreven in Hoofdstuk 4 Mammalian Toxicology, in Bijlage II bij dit besluit.

Het residuprofiel, de vastgestelde maximum residugehalten en de beoordeling van het risico voor de volksgezondheid staan beschreven in Hoofdstuk 5, Residues in bijlage II behorende bij dit besluit.


3.4 Risico voor het milieu

Het middel voldoet aan de voorwaarde dat het, rekening houdend met alle normale omstandigheden waaronder het middel kan worden gebruikt en de gevolgen van het gebruik, geen voor het milieu onaanvaardbaar effect heeft, waarbij in het bijzonder rekening wordt gehouden met de volgende aspecten:

  • de plaats waar het middel in het milieu terechtkomt en wordt verspreid, met name voor wat betreft besmetting van het water, waaronder drinkwater en grondwater,

  • de gevolgen voor niet-doelsoorten.

(artikel 28, eerste lid, sub b, onderdeel 4 en 5, Wet gewasbeschermingsmiddelen en biociden).

De beoordeling van het risico voor het milieu staat beschreven in Hoofdstuk 6, Environmental Fate and Behaviour, en Hoofdstuk 7, Ecotoxicology, in Bijlage II bij dit besluit.


3.5 Werkzaamheid

Het middel voldoet aan de voorwaarde dat het, rekening houdend met alle normale omstandigheden waaronder het middel kan worden gebruikt en de gevolgen van het gebruik, voldoende werkzaam is en geen onaanvaardbare uitwerking heeft op planten of plantaardige producten (artikel 28, eerste lid, sub b, onderdelen 1 en 2, Wet gewasbeschermingsmiddelen en biociden).

De beoordeling van het aspect werkzaamheid staat beschreven in Hoofdstuk 8, Efficacy, in Bijlage II bij dit besluit.


3.6 Eindconclusie

Bij gebruik volgens het Wettelijk Gebruiksvoorschrift/Gebruiksaanwijzing is het middel
Aliette WG op basis van de werkzame stoffen fosetyl-aluminium voldoende werkzaam en heeft het geen schadelijke uitwerking op de gezondheid van de mens en het milieu (artikel 28, Wet gewasbeschermingsmiddelen en biociden).




Degene wiens belang rechtstreeks bij dit besluit is betrokken kan gelet op artikel 119, eerste lid, Wet gewasbeschermingsmiddelen en biociden en artikel 7:1, eerste lid, van de Algemene wet bestuursrecht, binnen zes weken na de dag waarop dit besluit bekend is gemaakt een bezwaarschrift indienen bij: het College voor de toelating van gewasbeschermingsmiddelen en biociden (Ctgb), Postbus 217, 6700 AE WAGENINGEN. Het Ctgb heeft niet de mogelijkheid van het elektronisch indienen van een bezwaarschrift opengesteld.

A.
WETTELIJK GEBRUIKSVOORSCHRIFT


Toegestaan is uitsluitend het gebruik als schimmelbestrijdingsmiddel:

  1. in de onbedekte teelt van aardbeien;

  2. in de teelt van witlof op water.


Veligheidstermijn

De termijn tussen de laatste toepassing en de oogst mag niet korter zijn dan:

14 dagen voor aardbei.


Handmatig dompelen van aardbeienplanten is niet toegestaan


Het middel is uitsluitend bestemd voor professioneel gebruik.



B.
GEBRUIKSAANWIJZING


Toepassingen

Aardbeien, ter bestrijding van stengelbasisrot (Phytophthora cactorum) en roodwortelrot (Phytophthora fragariae).

WIJZE VAN TOEPASSING:

I. tegen stengelbasisrot (Phytophthora cactorum).

  1. DOMPELEN. De planten kort voor het uitplanten gedurende 15 minuten dompelen. Het dompelbad kan slechts één dag worden gebruikt, waarbij voorkomen dient te worden, dat het dompelbad te veel vervuilt. Na iedere dompeling de verloren gegane vloeistof aanvullen met een oplossing van de normale sterkte (0,25%). Voor elke dompeling het bad goed oproeren. De resterende dompelvloeistof mag uitsluitend worden verwerkt via een aangietbehandeling na het planten (max. 100 ml per plant).
    Dosering: 0,25% (250 gram middel per 100 liter water).

  2. RIJENBESPUITING. Direkt na het uitplanten en vastregenen een rijenbehandeling uitvoeren. Op vermeerderingsvelden kan op het moment van uitleggen van de uitlopers een volveldsbespuiting worden uitgevoerd in dezelfde dosering.
    Dosering: 75 gram middel per are in 10 liter water.

  1. tegen roodwortelrot (Phytophthora fragariae).

In de eerste week van oktober en ca. 4 weken later een rijenbehandeling uitvoeren. Het verdient aanbeveling om op zwaar besmette percelen een herbehandeling uit te voeren in het voorjaar (maart). Op vermeerderingsvelden kan na het uitleggen van de uitlopers een volvelds bespuiting worden uitgevoerd in dezelfde dosering.
Dosering: 75 gram middel per are in 10 liter water.

Witlof, ter bestrijding van verslijming veroorzaakt door Phytophthora spp. in de teelt op water.
Het middel direkt na het opzetten van de pennen toevoegen aan het proceswater. Het water daarna in circulatie brengen.
Dosering: 0,03% (30 gram per 100 liter water).

Local effects

Fosetyl-Al is not a skin irritant, nor a skin sensitiser, however, it is a severe eye irritant. Moreover, dermal irritation is observed in the repeated dose dermal study at the limit dose of 1050 mg/kg bw/d, without systemic effects. The NAEL for dermal irritation could be even lower than the overall NOAEL (via oral route: 500 mg/kg bw/d in the mechanistic 90-day rat study). It should be realised that the exposure of laboratory animals in the repeated dose dermal toxicity study is not comparable to the human exposure, mainly because the lab-animals are exposed under (semi)occlusion, whereas humans will be exposed to bare skin. This makes it very difficult to use the results from the lab-animals for human risk assessment.

Moreover, in this dermal toxicity study, the irritation effects were observed mainly at the 4-week observation, with some animals affected at the 3-week observation. Furthermore, the rats were exposed to 1050 mg/kg bw, at 10% of their body surface; assuming a body surface of 400 cm2 for a 200 g rat, this will result in an area dose of 1050 mg x 0.2/40cm2 = 5.3 mg/cm2. The estimated external human exposure is 160 mg at mixing and loading (the external exposure during application in strawberries is 180 mg, but this results in a lower area dose because a larger surface is exposed); assuming an exposed area of 2000 cm2, this equals an area dose of 160/2000 = 0.08 mg/cm2.


Taking into account the area doses, high NOAEL, and time of occurrence of effects, and comparing this to the use as described in the GAP (low frequency of application) and the lack of effects in medical reports, it is not expected that adverse local effects will occur in the unprotected operator and worker after dermal and respiratory exposure to fosetyl-Al as a result of the application of Aliette WG.

4.4 Exposure/risk assessments


4.4.1 Operator exposure/risk

According to the Dutch Plant Protection Products and Biocides Regulations the risk assessment is performed according to a tiered approach. There are four possible tiers:

Tier 1: Risk assessment using the EU-AOEL without the use of PPE

Tier 2: Risk assessment using the NL-AOEL without the use of PPE

Tier 3: Refinement of the risk assessment using new dermal absorption data

Tier 4: Prescription of PPE


Tier 1


Calculation of the EU-AOEL / Tolerable Limit Value (TLV)

For fosetyl no TLV has been set. The AOEL will be used for the risk assessment.


Since the formulation can be applied year-round (specifically in the culture of witloof chicory), a chronic exposure duration is applicable for the operator (including contract workers) and workers. A chronic AOEL is therefore derived and will be based on the NOAEL of 300 mg/kg bw/d in the 2-year studies in rats and dogs. Application of a safety factor of 100 results in a chronic AOEL of 3 mg/kg bw/day (= 210 mg/day for a 70-kg operator).


Exposure/risk

Exposure to fosetyl-Al during mixing and loading and application of Aliette WG is estimated with models. The exposure is estimated for the unprotected operator. In general, mixing and loading and application is performed by the same person. Therefore, for the total exposure, the respiratory and dermal exposure during mixing/loading and application have to be combined.

In the Table below the estimated internal exposure is compared with the systemic EU-AOEL.


Application of Aliette WG on strawberries will be achieved:

  • by dipping, shortly before planting. Strawberry plants are disinfected by dipping via drive-in vessels (forklift). Theoretically, strawberry plants can also be disinfected by manual dipping, but in current practice this hardly ever occurs in the Netherlands. Manual dipping is absolutely not advisable because the operator exposure is much higher than during mechanical dipping. Therefore, using the ALARA principle (an exposure As Low As Reasonably Achievable) to protect the operators against unnecessarily high exposure and taking into account that current practice in the Netherlands is mechanical dipping, the dipping of strawberry plants will be restricted on the label to mechanical dipping only.


Whole plants are completely dipped. The duration of one dipping cycle is 15 minutes. It is estimated that 24 cubic cases can be handled per day for mechanical treatments (drive-in vessels). About 40000 strawberry plants are treated in one day which is equivalent to a planting area of approximately 1 ha. Each plant needs 100 mL. This means that a maximum of 4000 L of dipping fluid has to be prepared per day (equivalent to 8 kg fosetyl-Al/day). Planting of the strawberry plants occurs automatically. The operator can only be exposed to Aliette WG during mixing/loading of the dipping fluid (the packing cases with plants are placed in and out the dipping unit with a lift truck). Therefore, a risk assessment is performed for the operator during mixing/loading.

The remaining dipping fluid can be poured on plants in the field.

  • via field crop sprayers, either row treatment or field treatment. Field treatment is considered worst-case, also for the pouring of remaining dipping fluid (see above).


Application of Aliette WG on witloof chicory (forcing on hydroculture) will be achieved:

  • by drenching (processing water). Chicory is grown in the field but tubers of chicory are cultivated indoors. After harvesting in the field tubers are placed in boxes indoors under dark conditions. New growth is initiated in a water/fertilizer solution (processing water). The processing water keeps the lower parts of the chicory tubers submerged. Information from the applicant: A big grower grows about 100 ha chicory/year i.e. 2 ha/week. Approximately 25.000 L processing water is needed per week i.e. 5.000 L/day. The dose rate is 30 g product/100 L processing water or 1.5 kg product/day (= 1.2 kg fosetyl-Al/day). The processing water is prepared in big tanks located in separate rooms or buildings. It is distributed via pump/hose system into the dark growth rooms and the tuber boxes immersing the tubers partly. Potential exposure of operators may only occur during preparation of the processing water.

4.4.2 Bystander exposure/risk

The bystander exposure is only a fraction of the operator exposure. Based on the low risk-index for the operator, no exposure calculations are performed for bystanders.


4.4.3 Worker exposure/risk

Shortly after application in chicory witloof it is not necessary to perform any re-entry activities during which intensive contact with the treated crop will occur. Therefore no worker exposure is calculated for this scenario.


However, shortly after dipping of strawberry plants, the plants are planted in the field with a planting machine. With this machine usually 3 or 4 rows can be planted at the same time. For each row a worker is needed to place the plants one by one in the machine. There is no model available to estimate the worker exposure during planting activities. As worst-case, the EUROPOEM II model for re-entry activities in ornamentals will be used. Per day, 4000 L of dipping fluid is prepared containing 8 kg fosetyl-Al. It is assumed as worst-case that 6 kg fosetyl-Al will be present on the 40000 plants treated per day (the same amount (6 kg/ha) is used for broadcast spraying on multiplication fields).

The exposure is estimated for the unprotected worker. In Table T.2 the estimated internal exposure is compared with the systemic EU-AOEL.

5.1 Summary of residue data

The assessment below is based on the DARs for fosetyl, the TNO report CTB-2006-013-RES (April 2006) and and the summary by RMS France for MRL harmonisation (April 2009, EFSA extranet).

Only points that are not covered by the List of Endpoints or that need clarification are discussed below.


5.1.1 Metabolism in plants

Metabolism studies in the crops category fruit has been summarised and evaluated in the DAR. Studies in apple and vine leaves were classified as leafy vegetables, which was considered acceptable in EPCO 19. It was also considered that the information on fruits and leaves available and the fact that the metabolism pathway is simple, no more information is considered necessary as not other metabolites are expected.


5.1.2 Metabolism in livestock

See List of Endpoints. The crops in the intended use are not generally used a livestock feed. Metabolism studies in laying hens are therefore not required.


5.1.3 Residue definition (plant and animal)

The residue definition for monitoring and risk assessment for products of plant and animal origin is: fosetyl-Al (sum of fosetyl + phosphorous acid and their salts expressed as fosetyl).


5.1.4 Stability of residues

Storage stability was studied in grapes, cucumber, potatoes and lettuce, which all have a watery matrix, as do the crops in the intended use. Fosetyl residues were proven to be stable during at least 12 months of frozen storage.


5.1.5 Supervised residue trials

Strawberry (outdoor)

Supervised residue trials in strawberry are available in the Draft Assessment Report on fosetyl. Twenty-seven supervised residue trials in strawberry in are available in TNO report 8378-res (April 2006). The most critical GAP of Alliette WG in the cultivation of strawberries is the treatment with maximally 3 applications of 6.0 kg as/ha with 28-day intervals and a PHI of 14 days.

Four trials are not acceptable as they were performed with one application of 40 kg as/ha and a PHI >29 days. The remaining twenty-three trials were performed with three (eight trials) or four (fifteen trials) applications. The trials with three applications were performed in accordance with cGAP-NL, except for the growth stage at last application, which was too high in some cases (85 or 87), and too short intervals but this is considered acceptable, as strawberries do not ripen simultaneously and are harvested over several days in summer. The spray interval is excepted from the 25% range and is considered acceptable. Trials represent an acceptable worst case.

In the trials with four applications, the first application was done with 0.2%; the three last applications were performed with 6 kg as/ha. For these trials, the same situation occurred regarding spray interval and growth stage at last application and the same conclusion holds true as for the trials with three applications. One trial is not acceptable as the PHI was too long (18 days).

The residue levels selected for MRL setting and risk assessment are presented in table R1.

The results from the accepted trials are in compliance with the current EU-MRL of 75 mg/kg.


Witloof

The intended use is the use on witloof chicory (roots) for forcing on hydroculture, with a cGAP-NL of one application of 0.024 kg as/hL PHI not applicable (application at BBCH 00-12). The cGAP-EU is more critical than the cGAP-NL with a foliar treatment in field (2x 4 kg as/ha, int 14d, PHI n.a. BBCH 35-47), after which roots are harvested. Consequently, the roots receive a spray treatment before forcing at the a maximum rate of 120 kg a.i./ ha and a PHI of 21 days. RMS France summarised and evaluated eight supervised residue trials in witloof in accordance with cGAP-EU. As the EU-MRL will be based on these trials, they cover the less critical intended use of Alliette WG.

The residue levels selected for MRL setting and risk assessment are presented in table R1.

5.1.6 Residues in succeeding crops

The recommendation from the List of Endpoints is adopted for the use of Previcur Energy in the cultivation of radish and lettuce:

Residues of phosphorous acid in the range of the LOQ (0.5 mg/kg) can be present for short time intervals between application and planting or sowing of a rotational crop. A pre-planting interval of 30 days is recommended

This is not applicable for the intended use of Alliette WG, as no rotational crops are expected to be planted within 30 days after removing strawberry plants after the last harvest of the fruits.


5.1.7 Residues from livestock feeding studies

The crops in the intended use are not generally used a livestock feed. Metabolism studies are therefore not required.


5.1.8 Processing factors

A processing study in strawberries has been provided. The study has been summarised by RMS France. Strawberries were processed into jam and canned strawberries.

The median processing factor derived from the studies is 0.5 for both strawberry jam and canned strawberries.


5.1.9 Calculation of the ADI and the ARfD

Calculation of the ADI

The ADI is based on the NOAEL of 300 mg/kg bw/d in the 2-year rat and 2-year dog studies. Application of a safety factor for inter- and intraspecies differences of 100 results in an ADI of 3 mg/kg bw/day (see the List of Endpoints for mammalian toxicology).


Calculation of the ARfD

No ARfD is derived, since fosetyl has no acute toxic properties.



5.2 Maximum Residue Levels

Temporary EU-MRLs are present in Annex IIIA of Regulation (EC) 396/2005.

The product complies with the MRL Directives/Regulation. Notification of revised MRLs is not necessary.

In the Standing Committee on Food Chain and Animal Health (SCFCAH) Pesticide Residues of 8-9 December 2009, a positive vote was casted on a Regulation amending, int. al. the MRL for fosetyl in radish. Although this revised MRL is not in force currently, the new MRL will be taken into account in the consumer risk assessment.


5.3 Consumer risk assessment

Risk assessment for chronic exposure through diet

A calculation of the Theoretical Maximum Daily Intake (TMDI) was carried out using EFSA PRIMo rev. 2.0, containing all available Member State diets, and the proposed EU-MRL in radish and temporary EU-MRLs. The maximum TMDI is 61.3% of the ADI for German children. The TMDI is 18.9% and 44.3% of the ADI for the Dutch general population and Dutch children ages 1-6, respectively.


Risk assessment for acute exposure through diet

As no ARfD was derived for fosetyl, a risk assessment for acute exposure was not performed.


Conclusion

Based on the assessment for residues, no risk for the consumer due to the exposure to fosetyl is currently expected.

The product complies with the Uniform Principles.


5.4 Data requirements

None.

6.1 Fate and behaviour in soil

Aluminium

At the request of Member State experts the rapporteur considered the potential impact of the additional Aluminium added to soil from the use of fosetyl aluminium compared to the amounts that occur naturally in soils. This consideration was included in the addendum to the DAR dated May 2005 and concludes that for soils at pH > 5 (most European cultivated soils), aluminium derived from fosetyl-Al is expected to be immediately adsorbed (ion exchange) and/or rapidly turned into insoluble forms and thus PECsoil for available aluminium are deemed to be negligible.

For soils at pH < 5, aluminium derived from fosetyl-Al is expected to join the exchangeable fraction. For the highest annual rate of application applied for as an intended use (28 kg fosetyl-Al ha-1 yr-1 to citrus without interception), the concentration that would result in soil is negligible compared to natural exchangeable aluminium present in soil. In addition the annual application is in the same order of magnitude as atmospheric deposition and it corresponds to the lower values for natural downward fluxes of aluminium in acidic soils. Accordingly aluminium resulting from the use of fosetyl-Al is expected to have no significant impact on the environment.


6.1.1 Persistence in soil

Article 2.8 of the Plant Protection Products and Biocides Regulations (RGB) describes the authorisation criterion persistence. If for the evaluation of the product a higher tier risk assessment is necessary, a standard is to be set according to the MPC-INS1 method. Currently this method equals the method described in the Technical Guidance Document (TGD). Additional guidance is presented in RIVM2-report 601782001/20073.


For the current application this means the following:


Fosetyl-Aluminium is a salt. The true active substance is fosetyl. The laboratory DT50 value for fosetyl is 3 hours (0.13 days). The mean DT50-value of the a.i. can thus be established to be <90 days. Furthermore it can be excluded that after 100 days there will be more than 70% bound (non-extractable) residues of the initial dose together with the formation of less than 5% CO2 of the initial dose.


For the metabolite phosphorous acid the following DT50-values are available: 157, 119, and 49 days (geomean 97 days).

Due to the exceeding of the threshold value of 60 days for the geomean DT50 (lab) for metabolite, it must be demonstrated by means of field dissipation studies that the field DT50 is < 90 days. No field data are provided.


Ethanol (max. about 78 %AR after 1.5 hours) and two unknown degradation products (max. 12.8 and 17.2 % AR after < 1 h) were characterised as being derived from the ethyl moiety. Because these unidentified metabolites were transient and were only detected on the first day, no risk assessment for is required in this case.


Based on the above, the proposed applications of the pesticide Aliette WG in principle do not meet the standards for persistence as laid down in the RGB, because of the high DT50 value of phosphorous acid. However, it is considered not convenient to require field data nor to derive a MPC-INS value for phosphoric acid, as the background concentration in soil as well as the amount added by nutrients exceeds by far the amount of phosphorous acid added by the use of the active substance fosetyl.


In this way, the standards for persistence as laid down in the RGB are met.

      1. Leaching to shallow groundwater

Article 2.9 of the Plant Protection Products and Biocides Regulations (RGB) describes the authorisation criterion leaching to groundwater.

The leaching potential of the active substance (and metabolites) is calculated in the first tier using Pearl 3.3.3 and the FOCUS Kremsmünster scenario. Input variables are the actual worst-case application rate [6-8 kg/ha], the crop [strawberries] and an interception value appropriate to the crop of [0-0.3]. First date of yearly application is May 25th. For the dipping treatment an incorporation depth of 5 cm is assumed.

For metabolites all available data concerning substance properties are regarded.

Metabolite phosphorous acid from fosetyl is included in the calculations.

No formal assessment of the adsorption and leaching potential of the major soil metabolite ethanol was carried out. However because of its short soil half life (in the same range as the parent fosetyl-Al), the potential for ethanol to leach to groundwater is considered to be insignificant and is covered by the modelling carried out for the parent fosetyl-Al. (both compounds are highly water soluble with minimal adsorption potential so a Koc of 0.1 mL/g and 1/n of 1 would be an appropriate conservative modelling input value for ethanol as well as fosetyl-Al).

No other metabolites occurred above > 10 % of AR, > 5 % of AR at two consecutive sample points or had an increasing tendency. No calculation are performed for the use in witloof as this crop is grown on hydroculture only.

Based on substance properties (DT50< 10 days and Kom< 10 L/kg) for fosetyl, the first tier assessment with PEARL 3.3.3 is not suitable and the assessment should directly be based on GeoPEARL calculations. Because the DT50 of fosetyl is 3 hours, the expected leaching to groundwater will be negligible and calculations with GeoPEARL are not required.

6.2 Fate and behaviour in water


6.2.1 Rate and route of degradation in surface water

The exposure concentrations of the active substance fosetyl and metabolites phosphorous acid in surface water have been estimated for the various proposed uses using calculations of surface water concentrations (in a ditch of 30 cm depth), which originate from spray drift during application of the active substance. The spray drift percen­tage depends on the use. No drift reductions measures are mentioned in the WG/GA.


For the indoor use in witloof exposure cannot be excluded.

Aliette WG can be used as:

  • an application at the start of the forcing period

Assumptions for risk assessment are:

  • application at the start of the forcing period by adding 84 kg fosetyl-Al/ha.

  • Only exposure to surface water is relevant. An emission percentage of 0.1% is used.


Concentrations in surface water are calculated using the model TOXSWA. The following input data are used for the calculation:

PEC-WFD water body

Since an ecotoxicological risk cannot be excluded in the first tier of the edge-of-field ditch assessment, a second tier assessment has to be performed.

By decree of the Ministry of Agriculture, Nature and Food Quality, the Ministry of Housing, Spatial Planning and the Environment and the Ministry of Transport, Public Works and Water Management, Ctgb has to assess from September 2009 onwards –based on an interim assessment methodology, see C-212.6 whether an ecotoxicological risk in the Water Framework Directive (WFD) water bodies might occur. This is implemented by examining the MPC-INS (both acute and chronic values) against a calculated exposure concentration in the WFD water body.

In the interim period, only the maximum PEC in the WFD water body is considered (since more knowledge and consensus is needed before implementing a time-weighted average concentration).


The calculation of the PEC at the WFD water body accounts for dilution (dilution factor depending on the frequency of application) and degradation during the travel time from ditch to WFD water body. The formula to arrive at this PEC-WFD is:


PECmax, WFD = PECmax, edge-of-field ditch* e(-residence time*k) / dilution factor


With k=ln2/DT50system. In this case, the DT50 used is 4 days.


For predicted concentrations in the WFD water body see Table M.3b.

Monitoring data

The Pesticide Atlas on internet (www.pesticidesatlas.nl, www.bestrijdingsmiddelenatlas.nl) is used to evaluate measured concentrations of pesticides in Dutch surface water, and to assess whether the observed concentrations exceed threshold values.

Dutch water boards have a well-established programme for monitoring pesticide contamination of surface waters. In the Pesticide Atlas, these monitoring data are processed into a graphic format accessible on-line and aiming to provide an insight into measured pesticide contamination of Dutch surface waters against environmental standards.

Recently, the new version 2.0 was released. This new version of the Pesticide Atlas does not contain the land use correlation analysis needed to draw relevant conclusions for the authorisation procedure. Instead a link to the land use analysis performed in version 1.0 is made, in which the analysis is made on the basis of data aggregation based on grid cells of either 5 x 5 km or 1 x 1 km.


Data from the Pesticide Atlas are used to evaluate potential exceeding of the authorisation threshold and the MPC (ad-hoc or according to INS) threshold.

For examination against the drinking water criterion, another database (VEWIN) is used, since the drinking water criterion is only examined at drinking water abstraction points. For the assessment of the proposed applications regarding the drinking water criterion, see next section.

Fosetyl-Al

The active substance fosetyl-Al was observed in the surface water (most recent data from 2007). In Table M.4, the number of observations in the surface water are presented.

In the Pesticide Atlas, surface water concentrations are compared to the authorisation threshold value of 100 µg/L (C-80.3.13, decision of 1/11/1998, consisting of first or higher tier acute or chronic ecotoxicological threshold value, including relevant safety factors, which is used for risk assessment, in this case 0.1*NOEC alg) and to the indicative Maximum Permissible Concentration (MPC) of 100 µg/L as presented in the Pesticide Atlas (31-5-2007, data source for the MPC: Zoeksysteem normen voor het waterbeheer, http://www.helpdeskwater.nl/normen_zoeksysteem/normen.php).


Currently, this MPC value is not harmonised, which means that not all available ecotoxicological data for this substance are included in the threshold value. In the near future and in the framework of the Water Framework Directive, new quality criteria will be developed which will include both MPC data as well as authorisation data.

The currently available MPC value is reported here for information purposes. Pending this policy development (finalisation for all substances expected in 2009-2010), however, no consequences can be drawn for the proposed application(s).

Drinking water criterion

It follows from the decision of the Court of Appeal on Trade and Industry of 19 August 2005 (Awb 04/37 (General Administrative Law Act)) that when considering an application, the Ctgb should, on the basis of the scientific and technical knowledge and taking into account the data submitted with the application, also judge the application according to the drinking water criterion ‘surface water intended for drinking water production’. No mathematical model for this aspect is available. This means that any data that is available cannot be adequately taken into account. It is therefore not possible to arrive at a scientifically well-founded assessment according to this criterion. The Ctgb has not been given the instruments for testing surface water from which drinking water is produced according to the drinking water criterion. In order to comply with the Court’s decision, however - from which it can be concluded that the Ctgb should make an effort to give an opinion on this point – and as provisional measure, to avoid a situation where no authorisation at all can be granted during the development of a model generation of the data necessary, the Ctgb has investigated whether the product under consideration and the active substance could give cause for concern about the drinking water criterion.


Fosetyl-Al has been on the Dutch market for > 3 years (authorised since 30 September1997). This period is sufficiently large to consider the market share to be established. From the general scientific knowledge collected by the Ctgb about the product and its active substance, the Ctgb concludes that there are in this case no concrete indications for concern about the consequences of this product for surface water from which drinking water is produced, when used in compliance with the directions for use. The Ctgb does under this approach expect no exceeding of the drinking water criterion. The standards for surface water destined for the production of drinking water as laid down in the RGB are met.


6.3 Fate and behaviour in air

Route and rate of degradation in air

The active substance fosetyl-Al is little volatile. The vapour pressure is 1 x 10e-7 Pa at 20°C. The Henry constant is 3.2 x 10e-10 at 20°C. The half-life in air is 0.96 days.


Since at present there is no framework to assess fate and behaviour in air of plant protection products, for the time being this issue is not taken into consideration.

6.6 Overall conclusions fate and behaviour

It can be concluded that:

  1. the active substance fosetyl-Al meets the standards for per­sis­tence in soil as laid down in the RGB.

  2. metabolites aluminium, ethanol, and two unknown degradation products, can be excluded from risk assessment and meet the standards for per­sis­tence in soil as laid down in the RGB.

  3. metabolite fosetyl and phosphorous acid and meet the standards for per­sis­tence in soil as laid down in the RGB.

  4. all proposed applications of the active substance fosetyl-Al meet the standards for leaching to the shallow groundwater as laid down in the RGB.

  5. all proposed applications of metabolite fosetyl and phosphorous acid meet the standards for leaching to shallow groundwater as laid down in the RGB.

  6. all proposed applications of the active substance fosetyl-Al meet the standards for surface water destined for the production of drinking water as laid down in the RGB.

7.1 Effects on birds

Birds can be exposed to the active substance Fosetyl-Al via natural food (sprayed insects, seeds, leafs) and drinking water. For the indoor use in witloof, only drinking water is relevant.

The threshold value for birds is based on the trigger from the RGB. This means that Toxicity-Exposure Ratio’s (TERs) for acute and short-term exposure should be  10 and TER for chronic exposure should be  5.

The estimated daily uptake values (ETE, Estimated Theoretical Exposure) for acute, short-term and long-term exposure are calculated using the Food Intake Rate of the indicator species (FIR) divided by the body weight of the indicator species (bw), the Residue per Unit Dose (RUD), a time-weighted-average factor (fTWA, only for long term) and the application rate. Refinement herbivorous bird

The applicant submitted the following statement:

In the DAR a DT50 of 4.2 days is calculated from a study on lettuce, however, this was not used in the DAR. The applicant submitted the underlying data and calculation. The Ctgb fate expert concluded that the available data is not sufficient to calculate a specific DT50 but that the data clearly show a fast dissipation. It can however safely be assumed that the DT50 is < 5 days (agreed with fate expert). For indoor uses much higher DT50 rates are expected, however, for the assessment of Aliette WG, only outdoor exposure is relevant. With this DT50, the MAF is 1.0, the Ftwa is 0.33. The refined risk assessment is presented after the refinement options for insectivorous birds.

drinking water

The risk from exposure through drinking surface water is calculated for a small bird with body weight 10 g and a DWI (daily water intake) of 2.7 g/d. Surface water concentrations are calculated using TOXSWA (see paragraph 6.2.1). In the first instance, acute exposure is taken into account. The highest PIECwater is 42.93 g/L. It follows that the risk of drinking water is (LD50 * bw) / (PIEC*DWI) = (4997 * 0.010) / (0.04293 * 0.0027) = 4.3 x 105

Since TER > 10, the risk is acceptable.


7.1.2 Secondary poisoning

The risk as a result of secondary poisoning is assessed based on bioconcentration in fish and worms.

Since the log Kow of Fosetyl-Al < 3 (-2.1) the potential for bioaccumulation is considered low and no further assessment is deemed necessary. For H3PO3 the log Kow is -4.96.

Taking the results for secondary poisoning through fish and earthworms into account, the proposed uses meets the standards for secondary poisoning as laid down in the RGB.


Conclusions birds

The product complies comply with the RGB.

7.2.2 Risk assessment for bioconcentration

Since logKow of fosetyl-Al and metabolite H3PO3 is < 3, experimental data are not required. The risk for bioconcentration is small. Therefore the active substance fosetyl-Al meets the standards for bioconcentration as laid down in the RGB.


7.2.3 Risk assessment for sediment organisms

Fosetyl-Al is not relevant in sediment. Metabolite H3PO3 is expected to be relevant in sediment.

The NOEC value for Chironomus is 100200 µg/L. When this value is examined against the PIEC in water of 27.37 µg/L, the TER value is 3661, which is above the trigger of 10. Therefore, the standards for sediment organisms as laid down in the RGB are met.


Conclusions aquatic organisms

The proposed applications meet the standards in both the edge-of-field ditch as well as the WFD-water body.


7.3 Effects on terrestrial vertebrates other than birds

Mammals can be exposed to the active substance fosetyl-Al via natural food (sprayed insects, seeds, leafs), drinking water and as a result of secondary poisoning. For the indoor use in witloof, only drinking water is relevant.

The threshold value for mammals is based on the trigger from the RGB. This means that the Toxicity-Exposure Ratio (TER) for acute exposure should be  10 and TER for chronic exposure should be  5. Dietary toxicity is not taken into account for mammals.

However, as was indicated in the Dar en the addendum, a further refinement of the risk is required for T. pyri, since a high variability was found in the mortality data from the different studies.


Second tier

In an extended laboratory test, no effects on mortality or reproduction were found at 64 kg a.s./ha. Since the tested concentration is much higher than the proposed concentration, an acceptable risk is expected for T. pyri.


Additional species

For Poecilus cupreus and Aleochara bilineata no lethal or sublethal effects > 50% were found at 15 kg a.s./ha. For Coccinella septempunctata mortality > 50 % was found at 15 kg a.s./ha, but were < 50% at 9.6 kg a.s./ha. This concentration is lower than the application rate of 6.0 including the MAF of 2.3. However, as shown in section 7.1.1, a DT50 < 5 days can be assumed and the interval is 28 days. This means that a MAF of 1.1 can be used. Therefore the proposed application rate is below 9.6 kg a.s./ha. Although there is still some uncertainty about the DT50, there is enough margin of safety to expect an acceptable risk for all proposed applications.

The proposed application of the product therefore meets with the standards as laid down in the RGB.

7.5.3 Effects on soil micro-organisms

For glasshouse uses, management practice includes regular sterilisation of the soil, which prevents the formation of a natural soil organism community within glasshouses. Exposure to natural soils is not expected. Therefore no risk assessment is performed for soil organisms.

In the tested soils no effects are observed on nitrogen transformation and carbon respiration processes at relevant application rates of 1067 mg a.s./kg with the formulation Aliette WG. Since the reduction percentage is below 25% after 42 days, the standards from the RGB regarding soil micro-organisms are met. It can be assumed that metabolite H3PO3 was formed at relevant application rates during this study, since this metabolite is quickly formed by simple hydrolysis.


7.5.4 Effects on activated sludge

An EC50 value of >100 mg/L is available.

The trigger is set to 0.1* EC50 corresponding to >10000 µg/L. The concentration in the influent of the sewage treatment plant (STP) has to be examined against this trigger using the model application USES. However, to date there is no module available to calculate influent concentrations for most application types (with the exception of mushroom use, public gardens and amenity uses). However, considering the low toxicity, no effects are expected.

For field uses no exposure of activated sludge is expected. Therefore, the proposed applications comply with the standards for activated sludge as laid down in the RGB.


7.5.5 Effects on non target-plants

Recently a new view on the off-crop evaluation zone for non-target plants has changed the appropriate drift values (see Evaluation Manual, Chapter 7). The risk assessment for non-target plants is now based on an off-crop situation with a drift percentage of 4.7%. The exposure thus equals 0.047 * the application rate *MAF (in case of multiple application). MAF-values are taken from ESCORT 2. The exposure thus equals 0.047 * the application rate. For Drench applications and indoor applications, no exposure is expected.


A TER is calculated with the lowest EC50 value from a laboratory test with higher plants and the exposure concentration. The lowest EC50 is >80 kg a.s./ha for. See table E.15 for TER calculation.

7.9 Overall conclusions regarding ecotoxicology

It can be concluded that:

  1. all proposed applications of the formulated product Aliette WG meet the standards for birds as laid down in the RGB.

  2. all proposed applications of the formulated product Aliette WG meet the standards for aquatic organisms as laid down in the RGB.

  3. the active substance fosetyl-Al meets the standards for bioconcentration as laid down in the RGB.

  4. all proposed applications of the formulated product Aliette WG meet the standards for mammals as laid down in the RGB.

  5. all proposed applications of the formulated product Aliette WG meet the standards for bees as laid down in the RGB.

  6. all proposed applications of the formulated product Aliette WG meet the standards for non-target arthropods as laid down in the RGB.

  7. all proposed applications of the formulated product Aliette WG meet the standards for earthworms as laid down in the RGB.

  8. all proposed applications of the formulated product Aliette WG meet the standards for soil micro-organisms as laid down in the RGB.

  9. all proposed applications of the formulated product Aliette WG meet the standards for activated sludge as laid down in the RGB.

  10. all proposed applications of the formulated product Aliette WG meet the standards for non-target plants as laid down in the RGB



  1. Efficacy


This evaluation is partly based on the summary and evaluation of Aliette WG prepared by Linge Agroconsultancy on behalf of the applicant (report number Lds09bayer10).


8.1 Efficacy evaluation

This application concerns a re-registration. Aliette WG is a fungicide which is authorised for use in several crops in the Netherlands since 1995. For registration the use in strawberry and witloof is claimed. The corresponding dose rates remain the same and no changes in circumstances have occurred (cultivation systems, application methods, resistance development).


Dose justification


Strawberry

The proposed dose rate of Aliette WG in strawberry is and remains 0.25% for the dipping treatment, 75 g/are in 10 L water for the spraying and row treatment. No changes in circumstances have occurred (resistance development, cultivation systems, application methods) and therefore no change in efficacy is expected.

No dose response trials were performed.


Witloof chicory

The proposed dose rate of Aliette WG in witloof chicory (forcing on hydroculture) is and remains 0.03%. No changes in circumstances have occurred (resistance development, cultivation systems, application methods) and therefore no change in efficacy is expected.

In 7 trials conducted in The Netherlands from 1996 till 2004, also lower dose rates than the proposed dose rate of Aliette WG (0.03%, 30 g/hl) were tested: 7.5 g/hl (1 trial), 15 g/hl (6 trials) and 20 g/hl (6 trials). The results confirm, in particular the percentage infected roots and development of the root system, that 30 g/hl is the optimum dose rate for an effective control of Phytophthora erythroseptica in witloof chicory forcing on hydroculture.


Effectiveness


The Netherlands

In the Netherlands effectiveness of Aliette WG in controlling Phytophthora cactorum was tested in 9 trials in which 0.25% Aliette WG (claim) was applied by a dipping treatment just before transplanting and in 9 trials in which 7.5 kg/ha Aliette WG (claim) was applied by spraying, 1 to 5 times.

In Belgium effectiveness of Aliette WG in controlling Phytophthora cactorum was tested in 2 trials in which Aliette WG was applied by a dipping treatment just before transplanting and in 2 trials in which Aliette WG was applied by spraying 2 to 3 times.


Dipping – Phytophthora cactorum – strawberries- trials in the Netherlands

In 1 trial, the number of infected plants in plots treated with Aliette WG was significantly lower than the number found in the untreated control. In 1 trial, the percentage infected plants in plots treated with Aliette WG was significantly less than the percentage found in the untreated control.

The control of Phytophthora cactorum by a dipping treatment of Aliette WG was in 2 trials significantly less, in 2 trials significantly better and in 3 trials comparable to the control found in plots treated with the reference product based on dimethomorph. Aliette WG outperformed the untreated control in all trials.

The crop vigour in plots treated with Aliette WG was in 1 trial significantly less and in 6 trials comparable to the crop vigour found in plots treated with the reference product based on dimethomorph. The crop vigour in plots treated with Aliette WG was in 3 trials significantly better than and in 4 trials comparable to the crop vigour of the untreated control.


Dipping - Phytophthora cactorum – strawberries – trials in Belgium

In 1 trial, the percentage efficacy given by Aliette WG was significantly less than the efficacy given by the reference product based on dimethomorph. Aliette WG outperformed the untreated control.

In 1 trial, the percentage dead and suffering plants in plots treated with Aliette WG was significantly less than the percentage found in plots treated with the reference product based on dimethomorph and comparable to the percentage dead and suffering plants found in the untreated control plots.


Spraying - Phytophthora cactorum – strawberries - trials in the Netherlands

In 1 trial, the number of infected plants in plots treated once with Aliette WG was comparable to the number of infected plants found in the untreated control. The number of infected plants in plots treated 2-6 times with Aliette WG was significantly lower than the number of infected plants found in the untreated control.

In 1 trial, the percentage infected plants in plots treated once with Aliette WG was comparable to, treated twice with Aliette WG was somewhat less than and treated 3-5 times with Aliette WG was significantly less than the percentage of infected plants found in the untreated control.

The control of Phytophthora cactorum by one application with Aliette WG was in 6 trials significantly less and in 1 trial significantly better than the control found in plots treated with the reference product based on dimethomorph. Aliette WG outperformed the untreated control in 5 of the 7 trials.

The crop vigour in plots treated once with Aliette WG was in 2 trials somewhat less than and in 5 trials comparable to the crop vigour found in plots treated with the reference product based on dimethomorph. The crop vigour in plots treated once with Aliette WG was in 3 trials significantly better than and in 4 trials comparable to the crop vigour of the untreated control.


Spraying - Phytophthora cactorum – strawberries – trials in Belgium

In 1 trial, the percentage efficacy given by 2 applications with Aliette WG was comparable to the percentage found in plots treated with the reference product based on dimethomorph. However, the number of dead plants in plots treated twice with Aliette WG, the reference product based on dimethomorph and in the untreated control was comparable.

In the other trial, the percentage efficacy given by 3 applications with Aliette WG was comparable to the percentage found in plots treated with the reference product based on dimethomorph. The number of dead plants in plots treated 3 times with Aliette WG and with the reference product based on dimethomorph was significantly lower than the number of dead plants found in the untreated control.


In the Netherlands effectiveness of Aliette WG in controlling Phytophthora fragariae was tested in 1 trial in which 7.5 kg/ha Aliette WG (claim) was applied by a row treatment. Aliette WG was applied twice or 3 times.


Row treatment - Phytophthora fragariae – strawberries- trials in the Netherlands

The percentage infected plants in the untreated control was 100%. The percentage infected plants found in plots treated twice with Aliette WG early in the growing season was high (100%) and comparable to the percentage found in the reference product based on metalaxyl (100%) and the untreated control. The percentage infected plants in plots treated twice with Aliette WG (1 early application and 1 intermediate application) was low (0-15%) and significantly less than the percentage found in plots treated with the reference product based on metalaxyl and the untreated control. Plots treated 3 times with Aliette WG (application spread over the growing season) showed a very low percentage infected plants (0-2.5%) which was significantly less than the percentage found in plots treated with the reference product based on metalaxyl and the untreated control.

As a consequence, the crop stand and the total yield of treatments with a low percentage infected plants was significantly better or higher than the crop stand and total yield of treatments with a high percentage infected plants.


Witloof chicory forcing on hydroculture

From 1983 till 2004, 10 effectiveness trials with the proposed dose rate of Aliette WG have been performed in The Netherlands. Aliette WG was applied once at the start of the forcing period by adding it to the circulation water at the proposed dose rate of 0.03% (30 g per 100 L).

The number of trials was sufficient and the infection in the untreated control was in general high enough to make an evaluation possible.

In 3 trials, the effectiveness of Aliette WG was compared to the effectiveness of the reference product based on dimethomorph. In all 3 trials Aliette WG controlled Phytophthora erythroseptica in witloof chicory just as good as the reference product based on dimethomorph. In addition, the crop vigour, total yield and yield in quality class 1 and 2 was also comparable between both treatments.

Aliette WG was in 7 trials compared to the reference product based on fenamidone+fosetyl-aluminium. The percentage infected roots in plots treated with Aliette WG was in 3 trials significantly higher than and in 4 trials comparable to the percentage found in plots treated with the reference product based on fenamidone+fosetyl-alumium. The development of the root system in plots treated with Aliette WG was in 2 trials significantly less than and in 5 trials comparable to the development of the root system in plots treated with the reference product based on fenamidone+fosetyl-alumium.

The crop vigour, the total yield and the yield in quality class 1 and 2 was in general comparable between both products.

Aliette WG was in 7 trials compared to the reference product based on propamocarb-hydrochloride. In general, the percentage infected roots and the development of the root system in plots treated with Aliette WG was less and better, respectively, than found in plots treated with the reference product based on propamocarb-hydrochloride. The crop vigour, the total yield and the yield in quality class 1 and 2 was in plots treated with Aliette WG in general higher and better than found in plots treated with the reference product based on propamocarb-hydrochloride.


It can be concluded that Aliette WG is effective in the control of Phytophthora cactorum and Phytophthora fragariae in strawberry and in the control of Phytophthora erythroseptica in witloof chicory forcing on hydroculture


Conclusion

The product complies with the Uniform Principles because it does in accordance with article 2.1

control Phytophthora cactorum and Phytophthora fragariae in strawberry and Phytophthora erythroseptica in witloof.


8.2 Harmful effects


8.2.1 Phytotoxicity

Strawberry

In 17 effectiveness trials conducted in The Netherlands and Belgium, Aliette WG was either applied once by dipping at the proposed rate of 0.25 %, or 1-5 times by a spraying treatment at the proposed dose rate of 7.5 kg/ha or 1-3 times by a row application at the proposed dose rate of 7.5 kg/ha.

In none of the trials and in none of the Aliette WG treatments phytotoxicity or visible residue was observed.


Witloof chicory forcing on hydroculture

In 10 of the 13 effectiveness trials conducted in The Netherlands from 1983 till 2004, Aliette WG was applied at the proposed dose rate of 0.03% (30 g/hl). In none of the trials phytotoxicity was found.


8.2.2 Yield

Strawberry

In 1 effectiveness trial in The Netherlands in 1982 and in 1 effectiveness trial in Belgium in 2005, yield was determined.

In the Dutch trial, Aliette WG was applied once by a dipping treatment at the proposed dose rate of 0.25%. No significant differences in yield were found between plots treated with Aliette WG, the reference product based on dimethomorph and the untreated control.

In the Belgium trial, Aliette WG was applied 1-3 times by a row treatment at the proposed dose rate of 7.5 kg/ha. The yield in plots treated once and twice early in the growing season was less than the yield found in plots treated with 2 (1 early application and 1 intermediate application) or 3 applications with Aliette WG. The difference in yield was strongly related to the degree of a Phytophthora fragariae infection. All Aliette WG treatments had a higher yield than plots treated with the reference product based on metalaxyl and the untreated control.


Witloof chicory forcing on hydroculture

Because yield is strongly related to an infection with Phytophthora erythroseptica, this aspect has been discussed in the effectiveness section




8.2.3 Effects on succeeding crops or substitution crops

Aliette WG has no direct adverse effects on subsequent crops. There are therefore no restrictions on subsequent cultivation. Long years of practical use confirm this.


8.2.4 Effects on plants or plant products to be used for propagation

No data available for evaluation. On the basis of the long years of experience with Aliette WP / WG and in view of the good tolerance of the product for many species, adverse effects can be ruled out.


8.2.5 Effects on adjacent crops

In the trials for the official product testing, no unintended side-effects on other plants, including neighbouring crops, were reported after use of Aliette WP / Aliette WG.

Likewise with drift onto neighbouring crops, no adverse effects have occurred to date, and these are also not to be expected in the future.


Conclusion

The product complies with the Uniform Principles because it does not, in accordance with article 2.2., induce any unacceptable side effects on plants or plant products, when used and applied in accordance with the proposed label.


8.3 Resistance

Fosetyl – Al was first registered in Germany in 1979 for use in broad vine protection practice as Mikal in coformulation with Folpet. In February 1980, Aliette was registered (as the WP formulation). In other countries, there were already previous registrations of Fosetyl – Al fungicides. In spite of the broad registrations in many crops, no resistance of target fungi has yet been reported.

Thus Fosetyl – Al was classified by the FRAC (Fungicide Resistance Action Committee) in the group “Y Multisite activity” with the comment: “Generally considered a low risk group with no sign of resistance developing to the majority of fungicides. Cross resistance not relevant”.

In principle, resistance cannot be ruled out, but the probability of the development of resistance with the active substance Fosetyl – Al is regarded as slight.


Conclusion

The product complies with the Uniform Principles, article 2.1.3 as the level of control on the long term is not influenced by the use of this product because of the possible build up of resistance.


8.4 For vertebrate control agents: impact on target vertebrates

Because no vertebrates are controlled, this point is not relevant.


8.5 Any other relevant data / information / Data requirements

None.

The product complies with the Uniform Principles.


The evaluation is in accordance with the Uniform Principles laid down in appendix VI of Directive 91/414/EEC. The evaluation has been carried out on basis of a dossier that meets the criteria of appendix III of the Directive.
